HW 2 Cluster Analysis and Decision Tree Induction

Introduction

The purpose of this assignment is to use cluster analysis and decision tree algorithm to find out who wrote the disputed essays, Hamilton or Madison? Below Function EnsurePackage is used to install and load packages.

EnsurePackage <- function(x) {
  
  x <- as.character(x)
  if (!require(x,character.only = T))
    install.packages(x,repos = "https://cran.r-project.org/")
  
  require(x,character.only = T)
}
#Installing and loading required library
EnsurePackage("factoextra")
EnsurePackage("caret")
EnsurePackage("rpart")
EnsurePackage("rattle")
EnsurePackage("C50")

Method

The dataset was downloaded from blackboard and loaded into R.Then some pre-processing was applied to better understand data

disputed <- read.table("C:/Users/vishu/Documents/707-Datamining/Disputed_Assay_data.csv",
                     stringsAsFactors = F,
                     header = T,
                     sep = ",",
                     row.names = NULL)

#find NA values
sum(!complete.cases(disputed))
#Omit NA values
disputed <- na.omit(disputed)

#tranfer data into matrix so as to apply kmeans in future
dmatrix <- data.matrix(disputed[,3:length(disputed)],
                       rownames.force = disputed$author)

#Convert author name to abbreviations
disputed$authorabb <- substr(disputed$author, 1,2)

#Change rownames to have author abbreviations so that it is easier for us to visualize data
rownames(dmatrix) <- make.names(disputed$authorabb,unique = T)

The goal is to find whether hamilton or madison were authors behind disputed papers.

Using Clustering

Kmeans Clustering will be used first to find out which documents belong to which clusters. Eclust function from package factoextra will be used for clustering. Default settings will be applied first followed by tuning different parameters.

The model just created a single cluster. Now clustering will be applied based on reasoning.In the dataset there is also an additional author Jay and books jointly authored by Hamilton and Madison.Therefore, the kmeans algorithm will utilize 4 clusters for this experiment so that we can get a clear picture of the author and their works and to find out to which clusters the disputed work belongs. If hamilton is the real author then the disputed works should fall in hamilton cluster.

km_output <- eclust(dmatrix, "kmeans",k=4,nstart = 25)

Based on the graph observed above the articles authored by Jay has a separate cluster, however the goal of our assignment, to find out the real author behind disputed papers cannot be accomplished based on the output of this graph since the 3 clusters overlap. The collaborative work between hamilton and madison can be separated however it is not possible to determine the author of the disputed articles through this graph

Hierarchical Clustering

Hierarchical clustering too gives us mixed results as the disputed points are over overlapping clusters. Below is a dendogram and a visual representation of it using factoextra library.

d <- dist(dmatrix,method = "euclidean")
hc1 <- hclust(d,method = "average")
clust <- cutree(hc1,k=5)
plot(hc1,cex=0.6,hang=-1)

fviz_cluster(list(data=dmatrix,cluster = clust))

Perhaps decision tree will be able to provide better results.

Using Decision Trees

The dataset will be copied into 2 training set.Hold out method will be used to separate dataset into training and testing. Training set1 will contain 90% train and 10% test data then the model will be evaluated. The data for training set is high because after many trials this set provided a better result. A large dataset could accomodate all author type which was not possible with 70-30 set. Training set2 will contain 74 rows and testing will contain 11 rows of disputed data. The training set1 is made to ensure that the model predicts all the author outcome accurately. After a good model is obtained, the tuning parameter of model1 will be used in model2 which does not have the disputed author in its training set. The model with tuning parameter 10 and min split 8 gave better result than default. Below is visualization of model1

#Creating training and testing set
disputed.dec <- subset(disputed,select = -c(filename,authorabb))
disputed.dec$author <- factor(disputed.dec$author)
split.sample <- sample(1:2, size=nrow(disputed.dec),prob=c(0.9,0.1),replace = T)
dis.train <- disputed.dec[split.sample == 1,]
dis.test <- disputed.dec[split.sample == 2,]


#using tuning parameters
dt_model1 <- train(author ~.,data=dis.train,method="rpart",tuneLength = 10,metric="Accuracy",control = rpart.control(minsplit = 7))
fancyRpartPlot(dt_model1$finalModel)

According to the model the disputed papers have branched from the madison node. This model will now be used to predict the outcome of test data and metrics will be evaluated.

dt_pred <- predict(dt_model1,newdata = dis.test)
histogram(dt_pred)

table(dt_pred,dis.test$author)

The accuracy of this model is fair for a model that needs to predict four variables. Now a new model will be generated using the same parameters without the disputed rows and then this model will be tested on disputed rows to know who is the likely author of the disputed articles. Whether it is Hamilton or Madison. Below is the code for the new model and its visual tree.

#Creating training and testing set without disputed
disputed.dec1 <- subset(disputed,select = -c(filename,authorabb),author != "dispt")
disputed.dec1$author <- factor(disputed.dec1$author)

#using tuning parameters
dt_model1f <- train(author ~.,data=disputed.dec1,method="rpart",tuneLength = 10,
                    control = rpart.control(minsplit = 8))
fancyRpartPlot(dt_model1$finalModel)

Now disputed data is extracted and used in our prediction model. dt_model1f will be used to determine the author behind the disputed articles

disputed.test <- subset(disputed,author=="dispt")
disputed.test2 <- subset(disputed.test,select = -c(author,filename,authorabb))
dt_pred <- predict(dt_model1f,newdata = disputed.test2)
histogram(dt_pred)

Conclusion

Given the result of the histogram it is clear that the model has attributed most of the disputed papers to madison. Therefore according to decision tree analysis the original author of the disputed series is madison and not hamilton.
